§ Why ⦉
¶ ⦊
  ‖ We consider a multiple knapsack problem in which different
    knapscaks have different profits and weights. ⦉
⦉

§ Definition ⦉
¶ ⦊
  ‖ Denote by $[m]$ and $[n]$ the sets $\{1, …, m\}$ and $\{1,
    …, n\}$, respectively. ⦉

  ‖ Given $p: [m] × [n] → 𝗥$, $w: [m] × [n] → 𝗥_+$, $c: [m]
    → 𝗥_+$, find $x: [m] × [n] → \{0,1\}^n$ to
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ \begin{aligned} ⦉

      ‖ \text{maximize} & \quad \textstyle ∑_{i = 1}^m ∑_{j =
        1}^{n} p_{ij} x_{ij} ᜶ ⦉

      ‖ \text{subject to} & \quad \textstyle ∑_{j = 1}^n
        w_{ij}x_{ij} ≤ c_i , \quad i = 1, …, n᜶ ⦉

      ‖ & \quad \textstyle ∑_{j = 1}^{n} x_{ij} ≤ 1, \quad i =
        1, …, n ᜶ ⦉

      ‖ & \quad x_{ij} ∈ \{0,1\} \quad i = 1, …, m, j = 1,
        …, n ⦉

      ‖ \end{aligned} ⦉
    ⦉⦉

  ‖ The above is called a ❬generalized assignment problem❭. ⦉
⦉

